# root .gitignore
.DS_Store
*.env
.env.local
```

Each subfolder's `.gitignore` handles its own (node_modules, __pycache__, dist, etc.) — Git respects all of them together.

---

## Deployment — Does This Cause Problems?

No — most deployment platforms handle monorepos natively:

| Platform | Monorepo Support |
|---|---|
| **Vercel** | Set "Root Directory" to `frontend/` in project settings |
| **Railway / Render** | Point to `backend/` as the root |
| **Docker** | Each folder has its own `Dockerfile`, build from root |
| **GitHub Actions** | Use `working-directory: ./frontend` in your workflow |

You can even set up CI/CD to only trigger frontend deploy when `frontend/**` changes, and backend deploy when `backend/**` changes — using path filters.

---

## Bottom Line
```
→ Same product, small-mid team  =  Monorepo (your case)
→ Independent services, separate teams  =  Polyrepo